{"name": "django-pgcrypto", "metadata": {"name": "django-pgcrypto", "version": "3.0.2", "classifiers": ["Development Status :: 5 - Production/Stable", "Framework :: Django", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Topic :: Database"], "home_page": null, "license": "BSD-2-Clause", "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["cryptography"], "summary": "Python and Django utilities for encrypted fields using pgcrypto.", "upload_time": 1733371411}, "documentation": ["![CI](https://github.com/dcwatson/django-pgcrypto/workflows/CI/badge.svg)\n\n# django-pgcrypto\n\nA set of utility functions for dealing with ASCII Armor (http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2440.txt) and padding, and a collection of Django field classes that utilize these functions in a way that is compatible with pgcrypto functions.\n\n## Installation\n\n`pip install django-pgcrypto`\n\n## Quickstart\n\nThere are several encrypted versions of Django fields that you can use (mostly) as you would use a normal Django field:\n\n```python\nfrom django.db import models\nimport pgcrypto\n\nclass Employee (models.Model):\n    name = models.CharField(max_length=100)\n    ssn = pgcrypto.EncryptedTextField()\n    pay_rate = pgcrypto.EncryptedDecimalField()\n    date_hired = pgcrypto.EncryptedDateField(key=\"datekey\", auto_now_add=True)\n```\n\nIf not specified when creating the field (as in `ssn` and `pay_rate` above), fields are encrypted according to the following settings:\n\n* `PGCRYPTO_DEFAULT_CIPHER` (only `aes` is currently supported) - The default algorithm to use when encrypting fields.\n* `PGCRYPTO_DEFAULT_KEY` (default: `settings.SECRET_KEY`) - The default key to use for encryption.\n\nYou must also make sure the pgcrypto extension is installed in your database. Django makes this easy with a [CryptoExtension](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/ref/contrib/postgres/operations/#cryptoextension) migration.\n\n## Querying\n\nIt is possible to filter on encrypted fields as you would normal fields via `exact`, `gt`, `gte`, `lt`, `lte`, `contains`, `icontains`, `startswith`, `istartswith`, `endswith`, and `iendswith` lookups. For example, querying the model above is possible like so:\n\n```python\nEmployee.objects.filter(date_hired__gt=\"1981-01-01\", salary__lt=60000)\n```\n\n## Caveats\n\nThis library encrypts and encodes data in a way that works with pgcrypto's [raw encryption functions](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/pgcrypto.html#id-1.11.7.34.8). All the warnings there about using direct keys and the lack of integrity checking apply here.\n\nThis library also predates Django's [BinaryField](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/ref/models/fields/#binaryfield), which is why the fields are essentially `TextField`s that store armored encrypted data. This may or may not be ideal for your application, and a hypothetical future version might include a switch to store binary data.\n"], "modules": [{"name": "pgcrypto", "documentation": ["django-pgcrypto", "Dan Watson", "A pure python implementation of ASCII Armor, along with various", "padding and unpadding functions, all compatible with pgcrypto.", "Additionally, this module defines Django fields that automatically", "encrypt and armor (and decrypt and dearmor) values for storage", "in text fields. Values stored using these fields may be read by", "pgcrypto using decrypt(dearmor(col),...), and values stored by", "pgcrypto using armor(encrypt(col,...)) may be read by these fields.", "See http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2440.txt for ASCII Armor specs."], "functions": [], "variables": [{"name": "pgcrypto.has_django", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pgcrypto.has_django", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": [{"name": "pgcrypto.__version__", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.base.__version__", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.__version_info__", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.base.__version_info__", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.aes_pad_key", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.base.aes_pad_key", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.armor", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.base.armor", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.dearmor", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.base.dearmor", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.Decrypt", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.functions.Decrypt", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.Encrypt", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.functions.Encrypt", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.EncryptedCharField", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.fields.EncryptedCharField", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.EncryptedDateField", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.fields.EncryptedDateField", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.EncryptedDateTimeField", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.fields.EncryptedDateTimeField", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.EncryptedDecimalField", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.fields.EncryptedDecimalField", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.EncryptedEmailField", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.fields.EncryptedEmailField", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.EncryptedIntegerField", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.fields.EncryptedIntegerField", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.EncryptedTextField", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.fields.EncryptedTextField", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.pad", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.base.pad", "project": null}}, {"name": "pgcrypto.unpad", "xref": {"fqname": "pgcrypto.base.unpad", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "pgcrypto.functions", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [], "classes": [{"name": "pgcrypto.functions.CryptoFunc", "bases": ["Func"], "methods": [{"name": "pgcrypto.functions.CryptoFunc.__init__", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "*args", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "**kwargs", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "pgcrypto.functions.CryptoFunc.get_params", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns":